eal with have their homes/land on annual payments.  They have no income for up to 3/4 months at a time during the summer/winter.  At those times when they do have income it's in huge chunks, most of my farmers are above the median annual income for our area, but at those times their focus is going to be paying extra down on mortgages or purchasing more supplies for the farm.  It's a focus on building the farm, not protecting the farm.  <br>
<br>
Multiple heirs only makes situations worse, b/c if a farmer does leave a will, it's almost always &quot;all property left equally to all my children&quot; to avoid fights.  What that does, in my experience, is pit the ones who do work the farm against the ones who don't.  The taxes will fall on them all equally, but only certain children are receiving income from the farm.  So the non-farmers want the farmers to buy their part &amp; pay their taxes.  This rarely, if ever, can happen at once, which leads to a significant portion have to be sold off to settle the disagreements legally.  <br>
<br>
It is my opinion that farmers are much more impacted than those who inherit business empires b/c of the liquidity of the commodity they inherit.  If childA inherits stock and childB inherits a huge tract of land, then childA is much more capable of selling only that which would be needed to cover the debt, in the form of individual shares.  ChildB cannot split a corn field down the middle to only sell part significantly lessening the value of both pieces.<br>
<br>
Finally I don't believe Paris Hilton, once her elders are dead and gone, will have the slightest clue how to maintain that fortune.  Even if she hires someone who can, they'll end up skimming off the top while she overspends to the moon.  The only different between she and GW, IMO, seem to be their personal financial aptitudes.  GW can clearly handle personal finances, at the expense of the national deficit.  The origins of their money is all old family wealth. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=barmaley>Barmaley</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 318<br> <font color=#333333>(4/26/05 11:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3301.topic&index=102>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: please</span><hr size=1> Vanessa, I am watching TV, term life insurance is under 1 dollar a day with premium up to half a mill. I am not sure what kind of prices are there where you live, but assuming we are talking working farmers between 40 and 60 years of age that dont drink heavily, I doubt the insurance is that huge of a burden on them. If it is, then its problem with insurance rates and health care, not with taxation.<br>
