<br>
Not true.  Try getting your budget numbers from the CBO, rather than from Republican apologists.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;The united states has run trade deficits for most of the 19th century<br>
<br>
The difference would be the abandonment of Bretton Woods fixed exchange under Nixon in the early 70s, and the resulting implications for the fluctuating value of our currency. Essentially we've been existing on inflows of foreign capital since.  To maintain that capital flow, in the face of the likely decline of value of the dollar in the medium to long term, interest rates will have to rise significantly. That's a fact.<br>
<br>
Don't get me wrong, there are some good things about a devalued dollar.  It will be good for our exports, we'll repay the public debt in effectively cheaper dollars, and domestic goods will become relatively cheaper compared to foreign goods.  But higher interest rates, and higher overall domestic price levels are an inevitable consequence.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;the sky aint falling chicken little<br>
<br>
No sky is falling talk here.  I don't foresee economic armageddon. There is, however, a good deal of unpleasantness for the nation that can be avoided or mitigated with responsible government action. So far there's been anything but that. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kurakaikhan>Kurakai Khan</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 883<br> <font color=#333333>(4/27/05 2:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3301.topic&index=110>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: now we're back to where we started</span><hr size=1> Ok let me rephrase that for you Bumraz, if a budget surplus is not used to spend down the debt is it really a surplus? NO, surely you can't argue another way.<br>
